revision.text:
{{Refimprove|date=March 2017}} '''Acidophile''' (or '''acidophil''', or, as an adjectival form, '''acidophilic''') is a term used by [[histologist]]s to describe a particular staining pattern of cells and tissues when using [[haematoxylin]] and [[eosin]] stains. Specifically, the name refers to structures which "love" acid, and take it up readily. More specifically, acidophilia can be described by cationic groups of most often proteins in the cell readily reacting with acidic stains.<ref>Ross MH, Pawlina W. Histology : a text and atlas. 5. ed. Philadelphia, Pa.: Lippincott Williams & Wilkins; 2005.</ref>
It describes the microscopic appearance of [[cell (biology)|cell]]s and [[Biological tissue|tissue]]s, as seen through a [[microscope]], after a [[histological section]] has been stained with an [[acidic]] [[dye]]. The most common such dye is [[eosin]], which stains acidophilic substances red and is the source of the related term [[eosinophilic]]. Note that a single cell can have both acidophilic substances/organelles and basophilic substances/organelles, albeit some have historically had so much of one stain that the cell itself is called a [[Eosinophil granulocyte|eosinophil]].
==See also== * [[Anterior pituitary acidophil]] * [[Basophilic]] * [[Oxyphil cell (parathyroid)|Oxyphil cell]] * [[Eosinophil granulocyte]] * [[Eosinophilic]]
