{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}} {{Use British English|date=May 2017}} {{Infobox person | name = | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 17 August 1903 | birth_place = | death_date = {{death-date and age|23 July 1989|17 August 1903}} | death_place = | resting_place = | nationality = British | other_names = | occupation = Botanist, plant pathologist | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = | education = [[Cambridge University]] }}
Dr '''Charles Edward Foister''' [[FRSE]] (1903–1989) was a British botanist and plant pathologist. He was Director of Scottish Agricultural Scientific Services in Edinburgh from 1957. He specialised in lichens and fungi.<ref>http://kiki.huh.harvard.edu/databases/botanist_search.php?mode=details&id=82603</ref>
==Life== He was born in [[Cambridge]] in [[England]] on 17 August 1903, the son of Frederick W Foister and his wife Esther Elizabeth Smith.<ref>https://www.geni.com/people/Charles-Foister/6000000036410965267</ref> He was educated locally and won a place at [[Cambridge University]] graduating BA in 1925. He continued as a postgraduate taking a Diploma in Agricultural Science (1927). He later received a doctorate (PhD) from [[Edinburgh University]].
He was employed as a plant pathologist in eastern Edinburgh for all of his working life. He became the official plant pathologist for Britain in 1938.<ref>The London Gazette 8 April 1938</ref> He was an active member of the Botanical Society of Edinburgh.
In 1954 he was elected a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Edinburgh]]. His proposers were Sir [[William Wright Smith]], Stephen J Watson, [[Malcolm Wilson (mycologist)|Malcolm Wilson]] and [[Alexander Nelson (botanist)|Alexander Nelson]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Biographical Index of Former Fellows of the Royal Society of Edinburgh 1783–2002 |date=July 2006 |publisher=The Royal Society of Edinburgh |isbn=0-902-198-84-X |url=https://www.royalsoced.org.uk/cms/files/fellows/biographical_index/fells_indexp1.pdf}}</ref>
He died at [[Colchester]] in [[Essex]] on 23 July 1989.
He never married and was presumed homosexual.
==Publications== *''The Relationship of Weather to Fungus and Bacterial Diseases'' (1935) *''Descriptions of New Fungi Causing Economic Diseases in Scotland'' (1940) *''Dry Rot Disease of Potato'' (1952) *''[[Nora Lilian Alcock|Mrs N L Alcock]]'' (1972)
