[[File:Stromboli Eruption.jpg|thumb|150px|An example of a lava arc driven by gas slugs during [[Strombolian eruptions]].]] A '''gas slug''' is a conglomerate of [[Partial pressure|high pressure]] gas bubbles that forms within certain [[volcano]]es, the agittation of which is a key driving factor in [[Strombolian eruption]]s. They start out as small bubbles of [[gas]] inside of volcanic [[magma]]. These accumulate into one large bubble, which starts to rise through the [[Magma chamber|lava plume]]. Once this accumulated slug reaches the top of the column and comes in contact with air, it bursts with a loud pop<ref name="hvw-strom">{{cite web|title=How Volcanoes Work: Strombolian Eruptions|url=http://www.geology.sdsu.edu/how_volcanoes_work/Strombolian.html|publisher=[[San Diego State University]]|accessdate=29 July 2010}}</ref> because of the lower [[air pressure]], throwing magma into the air in the typical lava arc of a Strombolian eruption. This type of eruption is episodic, non-damaging to its source vent, and one of the slowest forms of activity, with the ability to sustain itself for thousands of years.<ref name="ut-strom">{{cite web|last=Cain|first=Fraser|title=Strombolian Eruption|url=http://www.universetoday.com/29645/strombolian-eruption/|publisher=[[Universe Today]]|accessdate=30 July 2010|date=22 April 2010}}</ref> Although the effect of gas slugs in lava is well understood, how they form is not well understood, but recent research suggests that they can form as deep as {{convert|3|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} under the surface.<ref name="sci-strom">{{cite journal|authors=Mike Burton, Patrick Allard, Filippo Muré, Alessandro La Spina|title=Magmatic Gas Composition Reveals the Source Depth of Slug-Driven Strombolian Explosive Activity|journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]]|year=2007|volume=317|issue=5835|pages=227–230|doi=10.1126/science.1141900|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/abstract/317/5835/227|accessdate=30 July 2010|publisher=[[American Association for the Advancement of Science]]|issn=1095-9203|bibcode = 2007Sci...317..227B|pmid=17626881}}</ref>
